Dimentionality Reduction with Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

In this section, we try to reduce dimention of this high-dimensional data and capture the important information by deducing it. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) does this by transforming the original data into a lower-dimensional one while regulating highly correlated variables together. This makes understanding the data easier.

Before performing PCA, the data needs to be scaled:

In[]:
scaled_hw1_input <- scale(hw1_input)

Let's see few variables of scaled data to observe the behavior.

In[]:
pairs(scaled_hw1_input, main = "Scatter Plot Matrix of Scaled Features")
plot(scaled_hw1_input[, 1], scaled_hw1_input[, 2], 
      main = "Scatter Plot of Scaled Feature 1 vs. Feature 2",
      xlab = "Feature 1 (scaled)", 
      ylab = "Feature 2 (scaled)")
In[]:
plot(scaled_hw1_input[, 2], scaled_hw1_input[, 3], 
            main = "Scatter Plot of Scaled Feature 2 vs. Feature 3",
            xlab = "Feature 2 (scaled)", 
            ylab = "Feature 3 (scaled)")

Although through these scatter plots, it does not seem convincing that normality and linearity assumptions are met for PCA, we move forward with it to see its performance.

We can perform PCA with built-in function of R:

In[]:
pca_hw1_input <- princomp(scaled_hw1_input)
summary(pca_hw1_input)

We can see the contributions of components on scree plot:

In[]:
plot(pca_hw1_input, type = "l", main = "Scree Plot")

From the loadings matrix we can represent PC1 approximately as;

PC1 = 0.101length.of.patch-0.624width.of.patch -0.071height.of.patch -0.624height.of.substrate +0.02height.of.solder.resist.layer -0.025radius.of.the.probe+0.054c_pad+0.019c_antipad -0.039c_probe -0.445dielectric.constant.of.substrate -0.038*dielectric.constant.of.solder.resist.layer

This implies that PC1 has high absolute values for width.of.patch, height.of.substrate and dielectric.constant.of.substrate which indicates that these parameters are the most influential ones affecting S11 value. Their signs are negative which is good because it means that they have inverse relationship with S11 magnitude and lower S11 values are better.

We also see that length.of.patch, height.of.solder.resist.layer, c_pad and c_antipad have positive contributions though not significant; and height.of.patch, radius.of.the.probe, c_probe and dielectric.constant.of.solder.resist.layer have negative contribution, again, not significant.

Barplot for PC1;

In[]:
barplot(pca_hw1_input$scores[,1])

We can analyze remaining PCs in the similar fashion. More generally, it does not seem as there is consistency among PCs in terms of key variables, i.e. while width.of.patch is significant for PC1, it does not seem as such for PC2. In addition to that, the signs of key variables also varies from PC to PC.

Since PC1 has the greatest of variance coverage, we take PC1 as reference component and accordingly, the key parameters that most influence the S11 response of the antenna are selected as width.of.patch, height.of.substrate and dielectric.constant.of.substrate.

Regression Modeling

To build a regression model, we need to select some critical frequencies as our output data. Since lower S11 magnitudes are better, let's see which frequencies generate the 10 lowest S11 value.

In[]:
magnitude_s11_long <- as.data.frame(as.table(as.matrix(magnitude_s11)))
colnames(magnitude_s11_long) <- c("Observation", "Frequency", "Value")
output_sorted <- magnitude_s11_long[order(magnitude_s11_long$Value), ]
lowest_10 <- head(output_sorted, 10)
print(lowest_10)

It is seen that frequency corresponding to V72 column has the lowest S11 value in the dataset and can be a good candidate to investigate.

So can V29 and V28 as they are among the lowest 3 frequencies.

Let's create output columns to be used in regression:

In[]:
magnitude_s11_v72 <- magnitude_s11[ ,72]
magnitude_s11_v29 <- magnitude_s11[ ,29]
magnitude_s11_v28 <- magnitude_s11[ ,28]

We start with V72 output and create corresponding training and test data. We divide 70% of the data as training and 30% as test data.

In[]:
set.seed(123) 
sample_index <- sample(1:nrow(hw1_input), 0.7 * nrow(hw1_input))
train_input <- hw1_input[sample_index, ]
train_output <- magnitude_s11_v72[sample_index]
test_input <- hw1_input[-sample_index, ]
test_output <- magnitude_s11_v72[-sample_index]
train_data <- data.frame(train_input, train_output)
test_data <- data.frame(test_input, test_output)
colnames(train_data)[ncol(train_data)] <- "S11_V72"

Now that we have training and test data separately, we can build the regression model by using all features.

I believe, it is also possible to select significant variables from PCs matrix and build the regression accordingly, however, I would like to see how it performs with whole data and I expect it to produce the same significant variables as it did in PCA part.

Model Performance and Interpretability

PCA approach does not seem to be very effective since we can only reduce to 8 components from total of 11. Furthermore, the PCs have low consistency among themselves. I would expect a consistency for key variables that are influential among PCs, however, we do not see this in terms of coefficients and also the signs of the variables also change, making it difficult to support the argument regarding the influence of a particular variable.

This might be due to the weak linear relationships between variables. PCA works best with linear correlations between variables since it tries to find linear combinations that maximize variance. When this assumption is unvalid, PCA might not be very accurate which I believe is the case for this data. Furthermore, it is not convincing that the data is Gaussian, hence it might be another factor contributing to weak performance.

Regression analysis works relatively well for predicting the S11 magnitude with acceptable R-squared value. However, the model and key frequency level for S11 do not seem to work for real and imaginary components as they result in large MSE. Although not explored in detail, separate regression models for real and imaginary components are needed. We cannot directly predict their values from the regression model of S11 magnitude data. In addition to this, the linearity assumption for linear regression model is not fully met which makes the model not ideal.

In conclusion, with these data it might be a good alternative to build the non-linear models and explore further.
